  "text": "The decoupling of tertiary interactions in the triple mutant could be explained if nonnative structures are populated when core tertiary interactions are weakened, as previously suggested by time-resolved footprinting studies [CITATION_1] . Our SAXS data also suggested that this is the case because extended (nonnative) intermediates (I U ) are more heavily populated by the mutants than the WT ribozyme (Figure S3 ; Table S2 ). As a further test, native-like and nonnative RNAs were separated using nondenaturing PAGE. As expected, mutants that appeared less compact by SAXS also had a higher probability of forming alternative, nonnative structures (Figure 6 ).",
